Section 3.3.1 #1 - Whats gone wrong with this code? gplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = blue))

The aesethic color is not a not associated with a variable if you wanted to have colors based on class for example modify syntax to color = class.

Why are the points not blue? The points are not blue because if you wanted that to be the case the correct syntax would be gplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = blue) so that the color doesnt relate to a variable but is the color to be used for all plotting.

Which variables in mpg are categorical? Which variables are continuous? (Hint: type ?mpg to read the documentation for the dataset). How can you see this information when you run mpg? Based on the documentation categorical have fixed values that are drop down - based on the docs that would be drv and class.

?mpg

Categorical: drv class year fl cyl trans

Continous: hwy cty displ

What happens if you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics? Both are applied

  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = year, y = hwy, color = drv, shape=drv))

What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name, like aes(colour = displ < 5)? It evaluates the expression and in this case returns true or false values.

What does the se argument to geom_smooth() do? displays the confidence level (the grey shadow) if it is false does not display.

?geom_smooth

Will these two graphs look different? Why/why not? No they should be the same they are different syntax to achieve the same goal.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
